<Layout title="Selling Brisbane Property from Interstate or Overseas: How It Works | Daniel Gierach Property" description="Many Brisbane property owners do not live in Brisbane. Here is how to sell remotely without being present: electronic signing, foreign resident withholding, PEXA settlement, and more." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json">
{
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I sell my Brisbane property if I live interstate or overseas?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Queensland law allows contracts of sale to be executed electronically, the Form 6 agent authority can be signed via DocuSign or equivalent, and PEXA electronic settlement means you do not need to attend Brisbane in person for settlement. A local Brisbane solicitor handles the conveyancing remotely. If you cannot sign documents yourself, a power of attorney can be arranged."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the foreign resident CGT withholding and does it apply to me?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "If you are a foreign resident for Australian tax purposes, the buyer is required to withhold 12.5% of the sale price and remit it to the ATO unless you hold an ATO clearance certificate. The clearance certificate confirms to the buyer that withholding is not required. Apply for the certificate as soon as you decide to sell, not after a contract is signed, as it can take several weeks."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Do I need a power of attorney to sell my Brisbane property from overseas?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Not necessarily. Queensland contracts can be signed electronically and Queensland solicitors can verify identity remotely using an Australian consulate or Justice of the Peace overseas. A power of attorney is most useful when the seller is unable to sign documents themselves, for example due to illness or circumstance, not simply because they are located overseas."
      }
    }
  ]
}
</script>

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

