        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 7 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling Brisbane Property from Interstate or Overseas: How It Works
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        You do not need to be in Brisbane to sell your Brisbane property. Here is how to manage the campaign, contracts, and settlement from anywhere in Australia or overseas.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>A significant number of Brisbane properties are owned by people who do not live in the city. Interstate investors who purchased years ago, expats working abroad, and families who inherited properties in the inner east all face the same practical challenge when they decide to sell: how to run a campaign and complete a transaction without being physically present.</p>

      <p>The good news is that Queensland's legal and conveyancing framework is well set up for remote sellers. Electronic signatures, digital settlement through PEXA, and Brisbane solicitors experienced in remote transactions mean there is very little that actually requires physical presence. What matters more than your location is whether you have the right agent and the right solicitor.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Choosing the right agent when you cannot visit</h2>
      <p>For a remote seller, the quality of agent communication is non-negotiable. You cannot attend open homes to read buyer feedback yourself. You cannot walk through the property the week before launch to check the presentation. You are entirely reliant on your agent to be your eyes, ears, and honest counsel throughout the campaign.</p>

      <p>Before signing a Form 6 authority with any agent, establish exactly what the communication cadence will look like. Weekly written campaign reports, with attendance numbers, buyer feedback, and the agent's honest read on where interest sits, are a minimum. Video walkthroughs of the property before the first open home, so you can see what buyers will see, should be standard practice. A dedicated single point of contact at the agency, rather than being passed between staff members, matters when you are in a different time zone and cannot call in at short notice.</p>

      <p>The Form 6 authority itself can be executed electronically using DocuSign or an equivalent platform. You do not need to sign a physical document or have anything witnessed in person. Most Brisbane agents will issue this digitally as a matter of course.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Signing contracts remotely</h2>
      <p>Queensland contracts of sale can be executed electronically under the Electronic Transactions (Queensland) Act. Both buyers and sellers can sign remotely, and the executed contract is legally binding. There is no requirement for either party to be in the same room or to use a witnessed paper signature for a standard residential sale.</p>

      <p>Your Brisbane solicitor will receive the contract from the buyer's agent or solicitor, review it with you via phone or video call, and arrange the electronic execution. In practice, this process is often faster than a traditional exchange, because there are fewer delays waiting for physical documents to move between parties.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The power of attorney option</h2>
      <p>A general or enduring power of attorney allows a trusted person based in Australia, often a family member, a friend, or in some cases the solicitor, to sign documents on behalf of the seller. This is most useful when the seller is genuinely unable to sign documents themselves, for example due to illness, cognitive decline, or a situation where electronic communication is not practical.</p>

      <p>It is not the right tool for simply being located overseas if electronic signing is available. A power of attorney adds a layer of complexity, requires its own legal preparation, and introduces a third party into decisions that you can make directly. Use it when circumstances genuinely call for it, not as a default approach for remote sellers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How a Brisbane solicitor handles remote conveyancing</h2>
      <p>Queensland solicitors are experienced with remote sellers and have established processes for identity verification, document execution, and communication across time zones. Identity verification can be done through an Australian consulate or embassy overseas, or through a Justice of the Peace in any state or territory if you are interstate.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor will conduct all the conveyancing work, including reviewing the contract, responding to requisitions, managing the settlement adjustment statement, and coordinating the PEXA settlement, without requiring you to attend any office. The key is engaging a solicitor early, before you sign the agency authority, so they can flag any issues with the contract structure or title before you are committed to a buyer.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The foreign resident CGT withholding: act early</h2>
      <p>If you are a foreign resident for Australian tax purposes, there is a withholding obligation that applies to property sales above a certain threshold. The buyer is required to withhold 12.5% of the purchase price and remit it to the Australian Taxation Office, unless the seller holds a valid ATO clearance certificate at the time of settlement.</p>

      <p>The clearance certificate confirms to the buyer that you are not a foreign resident for tax purposes and that withholding is not required. It is issued by the ATO and can take several weeks to process. The critical point for sellers is to apply for the clearance certificate as soon as the decision to sell is made, not once a contract is signed. Waiting until you are under contract creates a real risk of settlement being delayed or complicated if the certificate has not arrived in time.</p>

      <p>Whether you are actually a foreign resident for Australian tax purposes is a question for your accountant or tax adviser, not your agent or solicitor. The rules around residency for tax purposes are not the same as immigration residency and can produce some counterintuitive results. Get proper advice early.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Settlement: no physical attendance required</h2>
      <p>PEXA electronic settlement is now standard for residential property transactions in Queensland. Title transfers digitally on settlement day and funds are deposited into nominated accounts via the PEXA platform. There is no longer a physical gathering of solicitors and bank representatives in a settlement room, and there is certainly no requirement for the seller to be present.</p>

      <p>Your solicitor will notify you when settlement has occurred and confirm that the net proceeds have been transferred. The timeline from launch of your campaign to funds in your account is the same whether you are in Brisbane or on the other side of the world.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What to set up before you list</h2>
      <p>Remote sellers who prepare well avoid the most common delays. Before launching the campaign, confirm that you have engaged a Brisbane solicitor who handles remote clients, have determined whether you need an ATO clearance certificate and applied for it if so, have established a clear communication schedule with your agent, and have given your agent written authority to manage access for photography, staging, and open homes without needing to contact you for each visit. The more you can set up in advance, the smoother the campaign runs from a distance.</p>

